Forgot to mention that all validators get to vote on amendments. I'm working on a blog post to try & better assemble/articulate everything.
Historic data integrity is one of the main reasons why RCL (recently renamed "XRP Ledger") is using a blockchain in the first place.
The ledger headers then would disagree with the data in the database and a simple ledger_cleaner call would just remove these entries.
In an attack, validators CAN'T re-write history because they have no way of signing new transactions.
Validators produce signed statements for everything they do. If a validator does something wrong you have a signed statement of its failure.
Consensus is allowed to fail. Malicious servers will be disconnected & consensus resumes. Stalled forward progress is worst that can happen.
Validators that refuse to come consensus with each other are detected by other validators. Network operators (me) alerted of dishonest node.
Validating servers check authenticity, verify issuers public key, and check validity of corresponding signatures.
So there is consensus 1st (agree on set txns to become candidates and then figure out if we can all agree on a close time) then validation.
Consensus is cooperative, not competitive. Every validator is a node, but not every node chooses to validate.
Every server (node) produces the new ledger independently by deterministically applying the set of txns agreed to during consensus.
Consensus negotiates close time.
Because rules by which servers apply txns are deterministic, servers will execute in exactly the same way. Only possible diff is close time
All nodes check to make sure txns followed protocol rules (signatures match, account exists, etc). Every node executes consensus.
Anywhere else in the world is better than keeping it on Poloniex.
